<pre><code>&lt;article&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
        Have you ever heard of '&lt;a href="http://mustache.github.io/"&gt;mustache&lt;/a&gt;'? Not the kind that grows on your face and makes you look like a schnauzer. I'm talking about the web templating system with implementations available for a lot of popular programming languages like ActionScript, C++, Java, JavaScript, Objective-C, Perl, PHP, Python and Ruby. It is a "logic-less" system due to the lack of control flow statements like your beloved if..else conditions and loops. So to give it a try, I have created a simple project that uses Grails to serve mustache templates instead of the regular gsp files.
    &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;!-- more --&gt;
    &lt;h2&gt;Foreword&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
        I'd like to point out that this is an experimental project to familiarize myself with backend Grails and Mustache at the same time. If you find any mistakes in my code or you can point out a better approach to this, please don't hesitate to inform me. I will post a link to the source code on my github repository at the end of this blog. Thanks to &lt;a href="https://github.com/edvinasbartkus/grails-mustache"&gt;edvinasbartkus&lt;/a&gt;, I used his idea to render Mustache templates, he has a different approach to this, you can check out his work over at github. Now let's begin!
    &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;h2&gt;Requirements&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
        The following are the list of requirements for this project:
        &lt;ul&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;Grails ver. 2.2.1&lt;/li&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;Mustache.java builder 0.6&lt;/li&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;MySQL 5.6 (this is optional)&lt;/li&gt;
            &lt;li&gt;Sublime Text 2 for text editing (you can use whatever text editor you like)&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;/ul&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Guide to growing a "Mustache" (Building our grails/mustache project)&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;span class="bold"&gt;Creating the project skeleton using grails&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
        We will be calling our experimental project "gTunes", a simple CRUD pages for managing song list. First off, we need to create our new grails project, you can do this by doing:

        <div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>grails create-app gTunes</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
    &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
        Let us also create our domain classes and controller that we will be using while we're at it:
</code></pre>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>grails create-domain-class com.gtunes.Song
</span><span class='line'>grails generate-controller com.gtunes.Song</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<pre><code>        We are using the generate controller command so that we could have our CRUD (Create/Read/Update/Delete) interface for our controller. You can use the grails create-controller if you like to start on an empty controller.
    &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
        After grails is done doing its thing, you can now go to the folder and open your project on you favorite text editor. For me I did:
</code></pre>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>cd gTunes
</span><span class='line'>subl .</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

